  "summary": "During an interrogation, Julia admits to Inspector Corrigan that she and Patrick lied about returning from Milchester together; she actually took an earlier bus at four o'clock and went for a walk through the fields. A telephone call from Mrs. Harmon interrupts the questioning, reporting that Miss Marple has gone missing from the parsonage and has not returned. Mrs. Harmon expresses fear and mentions a cryptic note Miss Marple left behind.\n\nBack at the house, Letitia Blacklock becomes distressed, and her pearl necklace breaks, scattering beads across the floor. While Phyllida suggests the pearls might be a gift from Randall Goodale, Cordeaux wonders if the pearls are actually genuine despite their appearance, noting that if they were real, they would be worth a fortune.\n\nCorrigan travels to the parsonage, where he meets Mrs. Harmon and Julian. They examine Miss Marple's note, which contains a series of disjointed phrases: \"Lamp. Violet. Where is the bottle of aspirin? Death of the Delicious. Consultation. Bravely bear the torture of pain. Iodine, pearl. Letti. Berni. Pension.\" Corrigan suspects the words may relate to Miss Blacklock's pearls. As he prepares to search for Miss Marple, Constable Fletcher calls out to him from a laurel tree.\n\nMeanwhile, at the estate, a tense dinner concludes in silence. Patrick feels his loss of favor, and Letitia appears exhausted and fearful. Julia maintains an air of indifference, expressing her desire to pack and leave, noting that she expects an arrest warrant to arrive at any moment.",
